    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In this article, we explored the beautiful worlds of stereographic projection and the Riemann sphere. There is a much more general topic of Riemann surfaces where we consider more general shapes than spheres known as manifolds. It is a beautiful and rich theory in itself.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If you want to play around with how different functions look on the sphere, I have created the following Geogebra sheet available <a href="https://www.geogebra.org/calculator/nhnnpuqf" target="_self">here</a>. You might need to fiddle a bit with the axes' lengths and the zoom to make it just right. To try a new function you can just change the definition of f(x). Try for example f(x) = zeta(x).</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
